message.content:
The start symbol S has only two possibilities:

1) S → NT2 NT29  
2) S → NT7 NT31  

The first word of the string is t2.  
Within the whole grammar the only non-terminals that can produce the
terminal t2 directly are NT3 and NT7; no other non-terminal has t2
among its terminal productions.

────────────────────────────────────────
Case 1.  S → NT2 NT29
────────────────────────────────────────
Because NT2 is on the left, the very first terminal that any derivation
of S must yield comes from NT2.

•  NT2 has no direct production of t2.  
•  Every binary production of NT2 has its left child distinct from NT3
   or NT7, so the first terminal issued by NT2 can never be t2
   (NT3 would appear only as the right child of a rule
   NT16 → NT3 NT10, but NT16 itself can be produced by NT2 only as the
   right child in NT2 → NT16 NT2; hence its output can never be the
   first symbol).

Therefore no derivation with S → NT2 NT29 can start with t2, so this
case is impossible.

────────────────────────────────────────
Case 2.  S → NT7 NT31
────────────────────────────────────────
NT7 can indeed produce the first word, since NT7 → 't2'.

Thus the remaining 16 words must be produced by NT31, whose leftmost
terminal must consequently be t72.

Inspecting every rule for NT31 one finds that the only way its
left-most terminal can be t72 is via

 NT31 → NT0 NT24 with NT0 → 't72'.

After NT0 has generated t72, the next terminal of the sentence must be
the very first terminal produced by NT24.  Looking at all possibilities
for NT24:

 NT24 → NT7 NT15  (first terminal ∈ {t52,t38,t35,t2,t11,t87})  
 NT24 → NT23 NT21 (first terminal ∈ {t64,t33,t20,t4})  
 NT24 → NT8 NT30  (first terminal ∈ {t53,t36,t24,t82,t45,t81})  
 NT24 → NT24 NT8   (recurses to the same sets)  
 NT24 → terminal   (terminals ∈ {t76,t42,t31,t55,t0,t68,t30,t87,t29})

None of these sets contains t37, the second word that has to follow
t72 in the target string.  Hence NT24 can never begin with t37, so the
derivation S → NT7 NT31 is impossible as well.

────────────────────────────────────────
Since neither of the two possible productions for S can yield a
sentence whose first two words are t2 t72 (let alone the complete
17-word string), the given string is not generated by the grammar.

No

The grammar contains several non-terminals that can:

1. Generate any of the terminals appearing in the string (every token in the given string occurs as the right-hand side of at least one lexical rule, e.g. NT20 → 't48', NT31 → 't87', NT7 → 't11', …).
2. Recursively build arbitrarily long sequences of such terminals.  
   Examples:  
   • NT29 → NT29 NT12 (with NT12 able to reduce to many single terminals)  
   • NT24 → NT24 NT8 (NT8 covers further terminals)  
   • NT23 → NT23 NT9 (NT9 reduces to terminals)  
   • NT2 → NT16 NT2, NT18 → NT18 NT1, …  

Because the start symbol S can expand to pairs that contain these unbounded generators (e.g. S → NT2 NT29 or S → NT7 NT31) and those generators in turn can recursively lengthen the derivation while freely choosing any needed terminal, the grammar can form an ordered sequence of any desired length consisting of any desired terminals from the grammar’s alphabet.

Hence a derivation exists that yields the exact 49-token sequence shown.

Yes
